The figure shows the potential profile and the corresponding energy eigenvalues for the case of **(n = 50) potential barriers** inside the infinite well.

The **black rectangular pattern** represents the potential (V(x)). Each spike corresponds to a barrier of height (V_0) and width (a), separated by free regions of the same width. Because there are many barriers, the potential structure becomes highly repetitive, resembling a **one-dimensional periodic lattice** similar to those used to model electrons in crystals.

The **red horizontal lines** represent the allowed **energy eigenvalues** (bound states) of the particle in this potential. Instead of appearing as a simple discrete spectrum like a particle in a box, the eigenvalues begin to **cluster into dense regions** separated by **clear gaps where no energy levels appear**.

These dense regions correspond to **allowed energy bands**, while the empty regions correspond to **band gaps (forbidden energies)**. This behavior emerges because the repeated scattering of the wavefunction from many regularly spaced barriers mimics the effect of a periodic potential. As predicted by **Bloch-type behavior in periodic systems**, the spectrum reorganizes into bands rather than isolated levels.

At **low energies**, the states are strongly influenced by the barriers, producing narrower allowed regions. As the energy increases, the allowed bands become **wider and contain more states**, because higher-energy particles are less affected by the barriers and can propagate more easily through the structure.

Overall, this result demonstrates how increasing the number of internal barriers causes the system to transition from a simple **finite-well spectrum** to a **band-like structure**, qualitatively similar to the energy bands observed in solid-state physics.
